03966nam a22005055i 9780773575752DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735757527 a10.1515/97807735757522doi  a(DE-B1597)654561  a(OCoLC)1394872209  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDC373.J8bY68 2009eb 7aART0150002bisacsh04a327.440921 aYoung, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican By Degrees :bThe Extraordinary Lives of French Ambassador Jules Jusserand /cRobert J. Young. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b12 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction and Acknowledgments -- tGenesis (1855–1903) -- tDebutant to Doyen (1903–1913) -- tCautious Seduction (1914–1917) -- tHesitant Embrace (1917–1918) -- tOld Arguments, New Quarrels (1919–1921) -- tThe Impassable Road to Separation (1921–1924) -- tCreation and Remembrance -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSource Materials -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe expressions of American hostility toward France after 9/11 are not new - Franco-American relations in the early twentieth century were also difficult, characterized by the same antagonistic depictions of the other's culture. Ambassador Jules Jusserand's years in Washington (1903-24) were defined by efforts to correct such misconceptions, whether they came from the venomous pens of French extremists or from members of William Randolph Hearst's press empire. In An American by Degrees Robert Young explores Ambassador Jusserand's life and legacy. Fluent in English, married to an American, and a historian who was a frequent guest at many American universities, Jusserand deftly cultivated American sympathies for France. His tasks as a diplomat were formidable, whether during the period of America's war-time neutrality - when France was nearly over-run by the German army - or when as allies they competed for control of the peace process or sought to resolve post-war issues like disarmament, war debts, and reparations. Jusserand relentlessly reminded Americans that France had been an ally during their Revolution and that their concept of "civilization" was part of France's intellectual and cultural legacy. His emphasis on their shared history was natural, as befitted the first winner of the Pulitzer Prize in History and only the second foreigner to serve as president of the American Historical Association.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357575240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773575752423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773575752/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles